04700nam a22006135i 9780520924352DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209243527 a10.1525/97805209243522doi  a(DE-B1597)647775  a(OCoLC)49851971  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBR190.H573bF73 2000eb 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a270.22211 aFrank, Georgia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMemory of the Eyes :bPilgrims to Living Saints in Christian Late Antiquity /cGeorgia Frank; ed. by Georgia Frank. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransformation of the Classical Heritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Pilgrims to the Living in Context -- t2. Desert Ascetics and Distant Marvels: The Historia as Travelogue -- t3. Imagined Journeys: Literary Paradigms for Pilgrimage to Holy People -- t4. Pilgrims and the Eye of Faith -- t5. How to Read a Face: Pilgrims and Ascetic Physiognomy -- t6. Pilgrims to the Living and the Memory of the Eyes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPilgrims in the deserts of Egypt and the holy land during the fourth and fifth centuries A.D. often reported visiting holy people as part of their tours of holy places. This is the first comprehensive study of pilgrimage to these famous ascetics of late antique Christianity. Through an original analysis of pilgrim writings of this period, Georgia Frank discovers a literary imagination at work, one that both recorded and shaped the experience of pilgrimage to living saints. Taking an important new approach to these texts, Frank finds in them a record of the writers’ and readers’ spiritual expectations and uses these fresh insights to add substantially to our understanding of the purposes and practices of pilgrimage.Frank focuses in particular on two important and well-known early texts—The History of the Monks in Egypt (ca. 400) and Palladius’s The Lausiac History (ca. 420), situating these narratives in their literary, historical, and spiritual contexts. She compares these narratives to exotic travel writing and to tales of otherworldly journeys. Bringing in contemporary theory, she demonstrates the importance of sight as a means of spiritual progress and explores the relation between the function of sight in these narratives and in other expressions of visual piety in late antiquity Christianity, such as the veneration of relics and, eventually, icons. With its unique focus on the sensory dimensions of pilgrimage—especially visuality—this absorbing book widens our understanding of early Christian pilgrims and those who read their accounts. At the same time, it also sheds new light on the relation between religious experience and the senses, on literary representations of visual experience, and on the literature of pious travel.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian pilgrims and pilgrimagesxHistory. 0aMonasticism and religious ordersxHistoryxEgypt. 0aMonasticism and religious orderszEgyptxHistory. 4aAncient. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aFrank, Georgia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022205240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092435240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520924352423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520924352/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of Ca